description: From Middle English outen, uten, from Old English ūtan (“from outside, on the outside, without”), from Proto-Germanic *ūtanē (“from without, outside of”), from Proto-Indo-European *úd (“up, over”). Cognate with Middle Low German ûten (“out, forth”), German außen (“outside, out”), Swedish utan (“without, free from”). More at out.

adjectives.description: outen (comparative more outen, superlative most outen)

entries.meaning: (chiefly dialectal) Being from without; strange; foreign; peculiar.
(archaic or dialectal) Out; out of; out from.

verbs.description: outen (third-person singular simple present outens, present participle outening, simple past and past participle outened)

entries.meaning: (transitive, chiefly dialectal) To put out; extinguish.
